{"type":"message","id":"4c49cd05","parentId":"a191284c","timestamp":"2026-04-06T06:07:29.810Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Oh! The Gateway is listening ONLY on 127.0.0.1:3103, not on 0.0.0.0:3103 or :::3103. It's only listening on IPv4 localhost. That's why:- My ws-proxy can't bind to 0.0.0.0:3103 (it fails)- But the health endpoint on 3104 works separatelyBut wait - the health endpoint returned successfully which means the ws-proxy process (my new one) IS running and working on port 3104. But there's a conflict on port 3103.\n\nActually wait - I'm confused. Let me re-read:\n- openclaw-gateway is listening on 127.0.0.1:3103 (IPv4 localhost only)\n- My ws-proxy tries to listen on 0.0.0.0:3103 (all interfaces) - fails because gateway is using 3103So actually:\n- Gateway uses port 3103 - this is for its WebSocket API\n- ws-proxy should ALSO use port 3103 to accept client connections and FORWARD to Gateway\n\nBut now there's a conflict! Both want to use 3103.\n\nLet me re-read the architecture:1. Frontend connects to ws-proxy on port 31032. ws-proxy forwards to Gateway on... some port\n\nBut wait - the Gateway itself is on 3103. So how does the old system work? Let me check if maybe ws-proxy was connecting externally somehow, or maybe Gateway has a different WebSocket port.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The old ws-proxy was running successfully before. It was connecting to gateway on port... wait, it was also 3103. But it worked. Let's look at what PID was running before (PID 4338 from earlier):```\nai 4338  0.0  0.4 11512864 66956 ?      Ssl  12:15   0:00 /home/ai/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/bin/node /home/ai/openclaw-router/ws-proxy.js\n\n\n```\n\nThat was running before and working. But wait - according to the lsof output from earlier:\n```\nnode      5358   ai   25u  IPv4 1358156      0t0  TCP localhost:51244->localhost:3103 (ESTABLISHED)\nopenclaw- 5524   ai   22u  IPv4  953504      0t0  TCP localhost:3103 (LISTEN)\n```\nThis shows a connection from port 51244 TO localhost:3103. So ws-proxy WAS connecting to Gateway on 3103. But if both Gateway and ws-proxy need port 3103, something's off. The Gateway is bound to 127.0.0.1:3103 while ws-proxy must be binding elsewhere or using a different interface.\n\n```\n-- actual Gateway process (5524)\n-- old ws-proxy (4338) - how did it work?\n\nActually I realize I may have misread. Let me check again.\n\nLooking at earlier output: OLD PID that was killed was 4338. And at that time, port 3103 showed as occupied by PID 5524 (Gateway).\n\nSo there were already TWO processes using 3103:\n- Gateway (5524) on 3103\n- ws-proxy (4338) also on 3103\n\nBut that's impossible if Gateway already occupied it...\n\nWait, maybe ws-proxy was listening on 0.0.0.0:3103 and Gateway was on 127.0.0.1:3103, which could conflict depending on the system. Or maybe the Gateway WASN'T running when ws-proxy started. Let me check when Gateway started.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at netstat output:\n```\nLISTEN    0         511               127.0.0.1:3103            0.0.0.0:*        users:((\"openclaw-gatewa\",pid=5524,fd\n\n22))\n```\n\nGateway is bound to 127.0.0.1:3103 (localhost only). And my new ws-proxy is trying to bind to 0.0.0.0:3103 (all interfaces). This causes a conflict!\n\nBut wait - the health endpoint returns OK, which means the node process IS running... Let me check what's actually running:\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d61667c7abd431d3403c512795070","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep -E \"ws-proxy|node.*openclaw\" | grep -v grep"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"codingplan","model":"minimax-m2.5","usage":{"input":256,"output":959,"cacheRead":31232,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32447,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775455603743,"responseId":"019d6165ce6